2 Description of requirements

coxpaper

HRFigureYa6rHRs

Single gene cox analysis and plot like in PAPER.

Calculate HR and save to file as input for FigureYa6rHRs.

Fig. 3. Forrest plots of hazard ratios of survival associated alternative events in LUSC. A, Hazard ratios of top 20 genes with survival associated ES events. B, Hazard ratios of top 20 genes with survival associated RI events. C, Hazard ratios of top 20 genes with survival associated AP events. D, Hazard ratios of top 20 genes with survival associated AT events. E, Hazard ratios of top 20 genes with survival associated AD events. F, Hazard ratios of top 20 genes with survival associated AA events. G, Hazard ratios of 8 genes with survival associated ME events.

3 Application Scenarios

coxD.R.Cox1972

cox

coxmiRNA, LncRNA,

cox proportional risk regression model, proposed by British statistician D.R. Cox in 1972

Mainly used for prognostic analysis of tumors and other chronic diseases, but also used for etiological exploration in cohort studies

Univariate Cox analysis is used to explore the independent prognostic impact of individual genes.

Cox analysis can be used for transcriptome, methylation, miRNA, LncRNA, variable shear, etc.

6 cox Univariate Cox analysis

# Cox
# Read prepared data for Cox analysis
realdata <- read.csv("easy_input_4cox.csv", row.names = 1)  # /first column as row names

# 36
# View first 3 rows and 6 columns of data
realdata[1:3, 1:6]
##                 OS OS.time   CD52 SPARCL1  LAMP3   SGK1
## TCGA-05-4244-01  0       0 7.7442  5.3650 4.3688 5.7445
## TCGA-05-4250-01  1     121 6.8349  6.1926 3.8136 6.0640
## TCGA-05-4382-01  0     607 7.2452  6.4138 1.5216 5.5681
# Cox
# Initialize empty data frame to store Cox results
Coxoutput <- data.frame()

# Cox
# Perform univariate Cox regression for each gene
for(i in colnames(realdata[, 3:ncol(realdata)])) {  # 3/columns starting from 3 are gene expression
  
  # Cox
  # Build Cox proportional hazards model
  cox <- coxph(
    Surv(OS.time, OS) ~ realdata[, i],  # + ~ /survival time+status ~ gene expression
    data = realdata
  )
  
  # 
  # Get model summary
  coxSummary <- summary(cox)
  
  # 
  # Extract key statistics and store in results data frame
  Coxoutput <- rbind(Coxoutput, 
                    cbind(
                      gene = i,  # /gene name
                      HR = coxSummary$coefficients[, "exp(coef)"],  # /hazard ratio
                      z = coxSummary$coefficients[, "z"],  # z/z-score
                      pvalue = coxSummary$coefficients[, "Pr(>|z|)"],  # p/p-value
                      lower = coxSummary$conf.int[, 3],  # 95%/95% CI lower bound
                      upper = coxSummary$conf.int[, 4]   # 95%/95% CI upper bound
                    ))
}

# /
# Convert numeric columns (from factor/character to numeric)
for(i in c(2:6)) {
  Coxoutput[, i] <- as.numeric(as.vector(Coxoutput[, i]))
}

# p(p<0.05)
# Sort by p-value and filter significant results (p<0.05)
Coxoutput <- arrange(Coxoutput, pvalue) %>% 
  filter(pvalue < 0.05) 

# CoxCSV
# Save Cox results to CSV file
write.csv(Coxoutput, 'cox_output.csv', row.names = FALSE)  # /exclude row names

# Cox
# Read Cox regression results
Coxoutput <- read.csv("cox_output.csv")
head(Coxoutput)  # /View first few rows
##        gene        HR         z       pvalue     lower     upper
## 1 C20orf197 0.8692715 -4.525712 6.019249e-06 0.8180980 0.9236461
## 2     NEIL3 1.1857460  4.055551 5.001621e-05 1.0920261 1.2875091
## 3   PKHD1L1 0.9004394 -3.746543 1.792881e-04 0.8523693 0.9512203
## 4    DEPDC1 1.2006680  3.702220 2.137213e-04 1.0898739 1.3227251
## 5      PKIB 1.1656775  3.301101 9.630614e-04 1.0642626 1.2767565
## 6    KCNK17 0.8888971 -3.288202 1.008296e-03 0.8286362 0.9535403
# HR(0.921.15)
# Filter genes with significant HR (0.92 or 1.15)
plotCoxoutput <- filter(Coxoutput, HR <= 0.92 | HR >= 1.15)  

# 1Nature
# Plot 1: Using Nature-style color scheme (black error bars)
ggplot(data = plotCoxoutput, aes(x = HR, y = gene, color = pvalue)) +
  # /Add horizontal error bars
  geom_errorbarh(aes(xmax = upper, xmin = lower), color = "black", height = 0, size = 1.2) +
  # /Add diamond-shaped points
  geom_point(aes(x = HR, y = gene), size = 3.5, shape = 18) +  
  # HR=1/Add reference line at HR=1
  geom_vline(xintercept = 1, linetype = 'dashed', size = 1.2) +
  # x/Set x-axis breaks
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(0.75, 1, 1.30)) +
  # xlog2/log2 transformation for x-axis
  coord_trans(x = 'log2') + 
  # /Set axis labels
  ylab("Gene") +  
  xlab("Hazard ratios of AA in LUAD") + 
  # /Set legend and title
  labs(color = "P value", title = "Univariate Cox regression analysis") +
  # viridis/Use viridis color scale
  scale_color_viridis() +  
  # ggstatsplot/Use ggstatsplot theme
  theme_ggstatsplot() +  
  # /Remove grid lines
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank()) 
## `height` was translated to `width`.

# /Save plot
ggsave('plot1.pdf', width = 8, height = 9)
